## Tools Used

- Event Viewer (Windows).
- /var/log/ directories (Linux).
- Apache logs (Web server).
- -SIEM ingestion methods (Agents, Syslog, Upload, Port-forwarding).
- Detection rules and dashboards.

## Findings

- Logs are valuable but scattered.
- SIEM centralizes, normalizes, and correlates logs.
- Detection rules reveal hidden threats.
- Analysts must investigate alerts carefully.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Deploy SIEM for centralized log management.
- Continuously monitor and correlate logs.
- Create precise detection rules to reduce false positives.
- Use dashboards for visibility.
- Train analysts to interpret alerts.

## Conclusion

- SIEM is essential for SOC operations.
- It solves challenges of scattered logs.
- Provides correlation, real-time alerting, dashboards, and compliance.
- Strengthens defensive security with proactive detection and response.
